{"/service/ndnp/deu/batch_deu_batman_ver01/data/sn84020422/00514156220/1908022601/0356.xml":{"full_text":"SHORT AND SN\u00c2PP\u00cf\nITEMS OF INTEREST\nGLEANED BY OUR WASH\nINGTON CORRESPONDENT\nClever Hits on Big Men and Great\nQuestions Which are Uppermost\nin the Public E ye of theWeek\nCriticism of the Navy has become\nso much the fashion recently that the\npresident some time ago deputed\nRear Admiral Converse, now on the\nretired list, to go into the question\nfrom the standpoint of an expert and\ntell the truth for the benefit of the\npublic. It will be remembered by\nthose who have followed the naval\ndiscussion that a lot of so-called ex\nperts have made all sorts of charges\nagainst the navy from defective con\nstruction and material Ito lack of\nspeed and gun practice. The two\nlatter charges are, as almost every\none knows, unfounded. The Ameri\ncan navy now holds the record for\ntarget practice with almost all guns\nat almost all distances. Ship for\nship, the shooting average is better\nthan in any nation of the world, and\nthe speed of the later ships has\nproved in each class to be the high\nest that could be expected,\nthere are only two\nwarship where the American navy\nhas not kept in the first flight, as to\nspeed. This is in some of the\npowerful destroyers where the speed\nrecord is held just now by the Ger\nman and in of the\nIn fact,\nvarieties of\nvery\ncruising scout ships recently turned\nout by the English Admiralty. These\nare matters that come within the ken\nof the average layman. Admiral Con\nverse, however, goes into the\ntechnical details of construction,\nsays that some of the older ships of\nthe navy are undohutedly not up to\nthe latest models in construction.\nThey were experiments in their time\nas in reality all warships are. But\nthe practical lessons of the Russo-Jap\nanese war have been taken into\nsid\u00e9ration in all of the later naval\ncontsruction, and as to armor protec\ntion, load line, height of freeboard\nand gun portion, there is no fault to\nbe found with any of the American\nships.\nwould be able to hold their own with\nany navy in the world,\nhearing coming from a man like Ad\nmiral Converse, for he is an officer\nand a gentleman and a i\u00bb 2 ii who\nknows his profession infinitely better\nthan the professional magazine critic.\nmore\nHe\ncon\nSquadron for qsuadron, they\nThis is good\nce the Jockey Club has declared\nthat gambling is not the incentive in\nracing Governor Hughes seems deter\nmined to let them try taking their\nracing and their gambling separately.\nIf Mr. Taft gets elected the hardest\npart of the job will be for him to sit\nin the White House for four\nyears\nwithout getting out and travelling\nsomewhere.\nHarry Payne Whitney says that he\nnever borrowed a cent from Hetty\nGreen.\ngilded youth who can boast of his\nfailure in that direction.\nWell, he is not the only\nHaving taken all the credit for the\nrecent panic, it is about time for Tom\nLawson to begin a series of magazine\narticles on how he brought about the\nreturn of prosperity.\nThis report of Raisouli going on the\nsuspicion.\nstage is open to\nWe\nshould not think it would tempt a\nbandit chief who had handled\nsoms in real money.\nran\nMr. Harriman has discovered in\nspite of the fact that money talks the\npeople who get it have to help\nthe conversation a little some time.\nout\nIt is almost unnecessary for the\nMaryland legislature to\nvoters that there is no nigger in the\nconstitutional emendment woodpile.\nassure the\nConsidering the troubles that\nare\nlooming up for the next administra\ntion the wonder is that so many peo\nple should be hunting for a job.\nIn spite of the fact that the Leap\nYear is pretty well advanced, there is\nno indication yet who Miss Do\nis going to propose to.\nmoeracy\nJust as the\nconcert of Europe is\ngetting nicely tuned up the Sultan\ninsists on sucking a lemon in front\nof the bandstand.\nAndrew Carnegie says there is more\nin hard work than in luck,\nreally the results\nfactory.\nBut\nare no more satis\nIt probably is a source of regret to\nChancellor Day that the\nseason of\nbanquet oratory is drawing to a close.\nProsperity seems to have returned\njust in time to meet the Easter\nbonnet in the road and get held\nup.\nFEBRUARY TERM OF COUNTY COURT\nW. H. Cooper of Kenton Loses His Case Ag\nalnst Benjamin Bedwell\u2014Test Case For\nSelling Soda Water Wllhonl License\nFebruary Court of Kent County\nconcluded its business this week after\na busy session. In the number of petty\ncases were some of more or less in\nterest to Smymians. In the case of\nthe State of Delaware for the use of\nJohn H. Gooden vs. Frank H. Russell,\nbeing an action in summons in debt,\nto recover from the bondsmen of\nFrank H. Russell, a former constable\nof Kent county, in which he failed to\nturn over certain moneys received\nfrom a sale to the person making the\nfirst levy, there being two levies made\non the property. Judgment for\nGooden for $147.96.\nIn the case of Benjamin Bedwell\nvs. William H. Cooper, being an ac\ntion to recover for a lot of hay moved\naway from the Cooper farm by Bed\nwell, a tenant, without the consent of\nthe owner. Judgment for S30 was\nrendered for the plaintiff.\nA. B. Magee, counsel for J. L.\nFord, appeared before the court and\nasked it to reduce the amount of\nmoney to be paid by him for the\nmaintenance of his eleven year old\ndaughter, in the custody of his di\nvorced wife, who lives in Philadel\nphia, keeping an apartment house.\nInasmuch as Mr. Ford is keeping one\nof his children, a son, and offers to\nsupport his daughter, the court ordered\na reduction in the amount of the main\ntenance of the child from $26 per\nmonth to $10.\nThe test case in the indictment\nound Tuesday against Clarke Mc\nkeeping and maintaining a soda\nwater fountain without paying a\nlicense, was continued to the April\nterm, inasmuch as Chief Justice\nLore, who is an uncle of M. Clarke,\ndeclined to sit in the case, leaving\nJudge Pennewill alone.\nFor the second time, Saturday, in\nthe case of Jacob Russel, after being\nlocked out all night, the jury disa\ngreed, 7 to 5, and were discharged.\nRussell, who was indicted for sell\ning liquor to Elmer Melvin, applied\nfor release, his counsel, R. R. Ken\nney, citing numerous cases in which\nthe State had acquiesced after the\nond mistrial. The court, however,\nrefused to release the prisoner, ar f|\nheld him to $800 bail until next April\nterm of court.\nHarr\" W. Satterfield was released,\nit being shown that he did not solicit\norders for liquor but merely acceded\nto a request of some friends and or\ndered the liquor sent to them.\nIsaac K. Gooden's case was dropped,\nhe having proven that his cider was\nnot intoxicating.\nIn the case of Emory Scotten vs.\nAraminta Sullivan to\nloaned on a judgment in 1896, the\nplaintiff was awarded $58.74 with in\nterest from Feb. 15, 1906.\nsec\nrecover money\nLETTER TO 0E0. W. TURNER,\nSmyrna, Del.\nDear Sir: Say milk is worth 8c a\nquart.\nIf 1-3 water and sold at 8c, the\nmilk in it fetches 12c a quart.\nIf 1-3 water, 16c.\nIf 2-3 water, 24c.\nIf 3-4 water, 32c.\nThat's rather too stiff for milk;\nbut watered paint is sold in all those\nproportions.\nPure paint (Devoe) is sold for $1.75\na gallon.\nPaint' at that price and 1-3 white\nwash fetches $2.62 a gallon for the\npaint part of it.\nPaint 1-2 whitewash fetches\n$3.50 a gallon for the paint in it.\n3-4 whitewash fetches\n\"Paint\"\n$7.00 a gallon for the actual paint it\ncontains.\nAnd people are paying all these\nprices for paint, when they buy adul\nterated paints,\nonly 8 pure paints only one Devoe.\nYours truly\nF W DEVOE CO\nP* S. The Iron Front Hardware\nStore sells our paint.\nThere are 200 such\nPoisoned From Eating Ice Cream.\nDr. William F. Davis, who attend\ned a nuwber of persons who were ta\u00bb\nken ill while returning from the\nding anniversary of Mr. and Mrs\nHenry Wright, of St. Jones,\nopinion last night that r\nmatter had gotten in the ice cream\nwhich the guests ate at the dinner.\nFourteen of the guests were violently\nill, some being afflicted so severely,\namong them former Commissioner B\nH. Moore, that they fell to the floor!\nDr. Davis is treating four of the\nguests who are still ill, among them\nbeing Mr. and Mrs. Charles Morris\nand Miss Morris,\nout of danger.\ngave the\na poisonous\nAll, however,\nare\nCan You Believe Your Sensei\nWhen two of them, taste and smell,\nhaving been impaired if not utterly\ndestroyed by nasal catarrh, are fully\nrestored by Ely's Cream Balm, can\nalUhaT i! th u this remed y deserves\nall that has been said of it by the\nthousands who have used it? It ia\napplied directly to the affected air\npassages and begins its healing work\nat once. Why not get it to day\ndruggists or ma i| e d hy Ely Bros 56\nAll\nOUR NEW SIMPLEX\nTYPE-SETTING MACHINE\nI\n\n4L\nI\u00a9\no\nThere is now located in the compos\ning room of The Times a Style Two\nSimplex type-setting machine, manu\nfactured by the Unitype Company, of\nBrooklyn, N. Y. The Style Two Sim\nplex is the latest model of the only\nsuccessful type-setting machine on the\nmarket and is as pretty a piece of\nmechanism as ever graced a country\nprint shop. While it took brains, and\nlots of them, to build the Simplex,\nit is an extremely simple machine,\nand one can readily understand its\nworkings after seeing it in operation,\nThe machine is small and compact,\noccupying not much more space than\nan oro'nary parlor stove. The body of\ntne machine consists of two cylinders,\none above and rotating on the other,\nand in both cylinders, extending ver\nt'cally their full length, are ninety\nparallel channels, those in the lower\ncylinder forming the magazine into\nw ic type distributes from the chan\nnels of the upper and is stored for set\nting. The upper cylinder is filled au\ntomatically with type that has been\nused by a very ingenious part of the\nmachine called the loader. On one\nside of the channels in the lower cyl\ninder a series of steel strips are in\nserte These steel strips are called\nwar s, as they have the same\ntunctions as the wards of a lock,\nEach type is given a combination of\nrucks corresponding with the combina\ntion of wards in one particular chan\nnel As the upper cylinder revolves\non top of the lower cylinder the type\nrops very fa\u00dft into the channels of\ne magazine, and it is impossible for\nPRETTY WEDDING NEAR ELUKSTON'S.\nMiss Sarah Ethel Mabrey Becomes the Wife\nof Dudley Crossley At a Home Wedding.\nThe home of Mr. H. E. Mabrey,\nnear Blackiston, was the scene of a\nvery pretty wedding Tuesday, Febru\nary 18, at high noon, when Miss Sara\nEthel Mabrey became the bride of\nMr. Dudley Crossley, son of Mr.\nJacob Crossley. Mr. Jacob Crossley,\nthe\nbest man.\ngroom, was\nThe bridesmaid, Miss\nAnna R. Mabrey, sister of the bride,\nbecomingly atfired in white over\npink, and carried pink carnations.\nThe ribbon girls were Grace Pratt,\nHelen Sylvester, Elsie Pratt and Ma\nnilla Crossley. The bride was char\nmingly gowned in white silk and\ncarried bride roses,\nried under an arch of\nwas\nThey were mar\nevergreen, be\nhind which were banked pot flowers\nThe\nceremony was performed by\nRev. W. E. Habbard. Miss Pearl\nShort played the wedding\nAfter the\nmarch,\ndinner was\nceremony\nserved to about 150\nguests, after\nwhich the bride and groom left for a\nshort trip to Philadelphia and Balti\nmore.\nThe bride received\nbeautiful and useful presents.\nmany\nEarly Closing Movement at Dover.\nA movement to have all Dover\nstores close in the evenings at 6\no'clock except Wednesday and Satur\nday evenings has been begun by the\nclerks and their friends,,\nmovement was begun several\nago and was then defeated on the\nground that country people from the\nthickly settled agricultural neighbor\nhood about Dover could not get in\nthrough the week for shopping\ncept in the evenings.\nA similar\nyears\nex\nMagistrate SailerfUld of \u00bbover. Dead.\nMagistrate John Satterfield, fa\nther of Deputy Attorney General!\nJames M. Satterfield, of Dover, died\nat his residence there suddenly late\nFriday afternoon, aged 68\nHe was taken ill Wednesday evening\nafter returning to his home,\nwidow is also critically ill.\nHis\na type to enter the wrong channel,\nThe machine distributes faster than it\ncan be set so it is not necessary to\nthe distributer continuously.\nA keyboard similar to that\ntypewriter is located in front of the\ncylinders, each key being connected\nby wires with a small plunger at the\nbottom of the channel containing the\ntype the key represents. When a key\nis depressed the plunger ejects the\ntype upon a rapidly revolving disc\nwhich encircles the bottom of the\nchannels. The disc carries the type\naround to a spring wheel, the wheel\nbeing so constructed that it is capable\nof picking type from the disc at the\nrate of 400 a minute,\nleave the wheel they enter a typeway\nthat is located immediately in front\nof the operator, the typeway being\nabout two feet in length,\ntypeway is filled with words and sen\ntences the operator divides the long\nline of type into lines the width de\nsired for a newspaper or book. The\nshort lines are then automatically\npushed into a receptacle called a\n\"galley\" and the type is then ready\nto be printed.\nOne person operating the machine\nwill do the work of three printers that\nset type by hand, and, with an assist\nant to divide the lines the work of six\nprinters is accomplished,\nThere are many other wonderful\nfeatures of this machine that must be\nseen to be appreciated. A technical\ndescription would make dry reading,\nso we simply invite our friends to drop\nin and see the Simplex in operation.\nrun\non a\nAs the type\nWhen the\nRev. Alfred Smith's Fruit Farm.\nRev. Alfred Smith, whose peach\nWyoming was two\nyears ago found to be infested with\nSan Jose scale, has had the orchard\nreinspected and the entomologists pro\nnounce it absolute